</li>
<li>
<h1>[City]SmallBusiness (e.g., #DallasSmallBusiness)</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>ShopLocal[City] (e.g., #ShopLocalDenver)</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>[Neighborhood] (e.g., #EastAustin)</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>[City][Industry] (e.g., #ChicagoPlumber)</h1>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Industry Hashtags (3-5 Per Post)</h3>
<p>These reach people interested in your service category regardless of location. They bring in followers who may visit your area or refer others.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<h1>HomeRenovation</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>WeddingFlorist</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>PersonalTrainer</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>LocalDentist</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>SmallBusinessOwner</h1>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Niche Hashtags (3-5 Per Post)</h3>
<p>These are specific to the exact service or product in your post. They have smaller audiences but higher intent. Someone searching #KitchenRemodel is closer to hiring a contractor than someone searching #HomeImprovement.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<h1>KitchenRemodel</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>BridalBouquet</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>FitnessGoals</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>DrainCleaning</h1>
</li>
<li>
<h1>TileInstallation</h1>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>The Size Mix Rule</h3>
<p>Combine hashtags of different audience sizes. Use 2-3 large hashtags (100K+ posts), 3-5 medium hashtags (10K-100K posts), and 3-5 small hashtags (under 10K posts). Small hashtags have less competition, so your post stays visible longer.</p>
<p>Check hashtag sizes by searching them on Instagram. The post count appears at the top of the results page. Rotate your hashtag sets every few weeks to avoid shadowban risks.</p>
